Geographic and environmental setting. The collection was made from waters in the southern part of the Kermadec Ridge, in the southwest Pacific Ocean – c. 1000 kilometres to the northeast of the North Island of New Zealand . This is a part of a northeast trending volcanic arc, more than 1300 kilometres long, comprising up to 40 volcanoes, many of which are actively venting (
Wright et al ., 2006
). The barnacles were attached to vestimentiferan tubeworms growing on the northern wall of the southern-eastern caldera of the Wright Volcano. The substrate is mainly basaltic, with diffuse low-temperature venting ( 8–9 ºC) adjacent to the sampling site (de
Ronde et al ., 2007
).

